Let's zoom into the frame parsing layer. I want to understand if there's measurable benefit to using SIMD intrinsics for validating the 256-byte checksum across high-frequency ingestion. Here's the current scalar implementation:

```rust
/// Frame wire format (256 bytes total):
///   [0..8]   device_id (u64 LE)
///   [8..16]  timestamp_us (u64 LE)
///   [16..240] payload (224 bytes)
///   [240..244] reserved (4 bytes, must be 0)
///   [244..248] frame_seq (u32 LE, monotonic per device)
///   [248..252] payload_len (u16 LE, actual payload bytes used, rest zero-padded)
///   [252..256] checksum (CRC-32C of bytes [0..252])

#[inline(always)]
pub fn parse_frame(raw: &[u8]) -> Result<TelemetryFrame, ParseError> {
    if raw.len() != 256 {
        return Err(ParseError::WrongLength(raw.len()));
    }
    // SAFETY: slice is exactly 256 bytes, all reads are in-bounds
    let device_id = u64::from_le_bytes(raw[0..8].try_into().unwrap());
    let timestamp_us = u64::from_le_bytes(raw[8..16].try_into().unwrap());
    let reserved = u32::from_le_bytes(raw[240..244].try_into().unwrap());
    if reserved != 0 {
        return Err(ParseError::NonZeroReserved(reserved));
    }
    let payload_len = u16::from_le_bytes(raw[248..250].try_into().unwrap()) as usize;
    if payload_len > 224 {
        return Err(ParseError::PayloadLenOverflow(payload_len));
    }
    let expected_crc = u32::from_le_bytes(raw[252..256].try_into().unwrap());
    let actual_crc = crc32c::crc32c(&raw[0..252]);
    if expected_crc != actual_crc {
        return Err(ParseError::ChecksumMismatch { expected: expected_crc, actual: actual_crc });
    }
    let mut payload = [0u8; 256];
    payload[..payload_len].copy_from_slice(&raw[16..16+payload_len]);
    Ok(TelemetryFrame {
        device_id,
        timestamp_us,
        payload,
        checksum: actual_crc,
    })
}
```

